---
import Layout from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import networkData from "../data/network.json";

const githubUrl = networkData.links?.github;
const discussions = networkData.discussions ?? [];
const relatedProjects = networkData.relatedProjects ?? [];

const siteParts = [
  {
    title: "Overview",
    href: "/",
    body: "A compact version of the argument, meant to introduce the core concept without too much local jargon."
  },
  {
    title: "Memo",
    href: "/memo",
    body: "The longer written framing from which the rest of the site is derived."
  },
  {
    title: "Explorer",
    href: "/grid",
    body: "A toy interface for comparing nearby training worlds and seeing what the grid metaphor makes visible."
  },
  {
    title: "Reading lists and glossary",
    href: "/collections",
    body: "Reference pages for when you want terms, papers, and neighboring literatures rather than a guided narrative."
  }
];
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Why Data Counterfactuals exists, what it is trying to clarify, and where to respond or contribute."
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="page essay-page">
    <header class="essay-header page-header">
      <div>
        <span class="page-eyebrow">Project notes</span>
        <h1 class="page-title">Why this site exists</h1>
        <p class="page-lede">
          Data Counterfactuals is an attempt to make training-data questions easier to see and easier to compare across
          literatures that do not usually sit on the same shelf.
        </p>
        <p class="page-lede">
          The site is part explainer, part toy lab, and part reading map. It is meant to support a line of thought, not to
          present itself as a finished framework.
        </p>
      </div>

      <aside class="essay-side">
        <p class="note-label">Status</p>
        <h2>Still being shaped</h2>
        <p>
          The explorer works, the memo is stable, and the references are useful already, but the framing is still being
          pressure-tested. Corrections and disagreements are part of the point.
        </p>
        {githubUrl && <p><a href={githubUrl}>Follow the project on GitHub</a></p>}
      </aside>
    </header>

    <section class="essay-section">
      <div class="essay-main">
        <h2>What the project is trying to make easier</h2>
        <p>
          A lot of machine-learning writing moves quickly from methods to benchmarks to theory. That is often the right move,
          but it can leave people without a clean mental model for the underlying question: what changes when the training data
          change?
        </p>
        <p>
          This site uses the phrase <strong>data counterfactuals</strong> and the grid metaphor as teaching tools. They are
          meant to connect several areas of work without pretending the existing literature already uses exactly this language.
        </p>
        <p>
          The hope is modest but useful: if the common operation becomes easier to see, then it also becomes easier to compare
          technical methods with questions about bargaining power, data labor, or strategic intervention.
        </p>

        <h2>What each part of the site does</h2>
        <ul class="link-cluster">
          {siteParts.map((part) => (
            <li>
              <a href={part.href}>{part.title}</a>
              <p>{part.body}</p>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>

      <aside class="essay-side">
        <p class="note-label">Not the claim</p>
        <p>
          The claim is not that valuation, poisoning, distillation, privacy, and collective action are all secretly the same.
          The claim is that they become easier to line up once you keep the data intervention itself in view.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="essay-section">
      <div class="essay-main">
        <h2>Ways to respond</h2>
        <p>
          If something here feels misleading, if a literature is missing, or if the interface gets in the way of the argument,
          that is worth hearing. Feedback is useful precisely because the site is trying to hold several neighboring ideas in
          one frame without overclaiming.
        </p>

        {discussions.length ? (
          <div class="reference-grid">
            {discussions.map((discussion) => (
              <article class="reference-card">
                <h3><a href={discussion.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{discussion.label}</a></h3>
                <p>{discussion.description}</p>
              </article>
            ))}
          </div>
        ) : (
          <div class="empty-state">Discussion links have not been added yet.</div>
        )}
      </div>

      <aside class="essay-side">
        <p class="note-label">Contributing</p>
        <p>
          Precise complaints are especially helpful here: a misleading comparison, an omitted paper, an awkward phrase, or an
          interaction that encourages the wrong takeaway.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="essay-section">
      <div class="essay-main">
        <h2>Projects in the same orbit</h2>
        {relatedProjects.length ? (
          <div class="reference-grid">
            {relatedProjects.map((project) => (
              <article class="reference-card">
                <h3><a href={project.website} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{project.title}</a></h3>
                <p>{project.name === project.title ? "A neighboring project with overlapping concerns." : project.name}</p>
              </article>
            ))}
          </div>
        ) : (
          <div class="empty-state">No related projects have been listed yet.</div>
        )}
      </div>

      <aside class="essay-side">
        <p class="note-label">Related work</p>
        <p>
          The site sits near a broader conversation about data leverage, data labor, provenance, and model behavior. These
          links are there to make that neighborhood easier to traverse.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
